on, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Stanwidge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Standage  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Standage","meanings":["English:","probably a variant of   Standish  .","in Leicestershire and Buckinghamshire, the name may alternatively be from Stanedge Grange in Hartington Nether Quarter or Stanage End in Outseats (both Derbyshire); but evidence is needed for this. The placenames derive from Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>ecg</i> ‘edge, escarpment’."]},{"name":"Standish","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): habitational name from Standish (Lancashire, now part of Greater Manchester), from Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>edisc</i> ‘enclosure, enclosed park’. Standish (Gloucestershire) does not appear to have contributed towards the surname.","History: Myles Standish (<i>c.</i> 1584–1656) was a soldier of fortune, from 1620 captain of the <i>Mayflower</i> Pilgrims at Plymouth Colony. Little is known of his origins and early life, but in his will he claimed to be descended from a leading Catholic family, the Standishes of Standish, Lancashire, England. He also claimed to have been deprived of his inheritance, a claim not confirmed."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William Stanwidge was born in 1277, in Chorlton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. He married Mrs. William Stanwidge in 1301. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1277–":"1277–Surnud","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1303–Female":"1303–Surnud","1277–Male":"1277–Surnud","1303":"1303","1301":"1301","1277":"1277","1280":"1280","Barlow, Chorlton, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1277–":"1277–Kuollut","1280–Female":"1280–Kuollut","1303–Female":"1303–Kuollut","1277–Male":"1277–Kuollut","1303":"1303","1301":"1301","1277":"1277","1280":"1280","Barlow, Chorlton, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1277–":"1277–Décédé","1280–Female":"1280–Décédée","1303–Female":"1303–Décédée","1277–Male":"1277–Décédé","1303":"1303","1301":"1301","1277":"1277","1280":"1280","Barlow, Chorlton, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Sir William Stanwidge est né en 1277, à Chorlton, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a épousé Mrs. William Stanwidge en 1301. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Il est décédé à Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni."},"de":{"1277–":"1277–Verstorben","1280–Female":"1280–Verstorben","1303–Female":"1303–Verstorben","1277–Male":"1277–Verstorben","1303":"1303","1301":"1301","1277":"1277","1280":"1280","Barlow, Chorlton, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","lifeS